Description:—
Living cells and colonies not observed. Valves elliptical-rhomboidal, length 58–64 µm, width 18 µm, striae 
22 in
10 µm except middle three coarser, 
18 in
10 µm; striae weakly radiating to parallel throughout (
Figs 79–81, 83
). Areolae of middle 3–5 striae much coarser than others (
Figs 79–83
), but those on the secondary side more widely spaced than those on the primary side (3 striae in the space of 5, vs 6 regular striae) and there often 1–2 striae which are biseriate on the mantle near the center (
Figs 82, 83
arrows). (The terminal raphe hooks go toward the secondary side: 
Cox 2012
.) Areolae covered internally by ricae (
Figs 85–87
). Raphe central endings distant (
Figs 81, 82
), the central area small, elliptical, slightly eccentric, narrower on the secondary side (
Fig. 82
). Terminal raphe endings some distance from the apex, with a short hook (terminal fissure) (
Fig. 84
), both hooked toward the secondary side of the valve. A small hyaline area just beyond the raphe terminus with typically two striae at the end of the hook having several infilled areolae (
Figs 84, 85
). A more or less distinct longitudinal line of areolae along each side of the raphe-sternum, continuing along the secondary side to the end of the hyaline area (
Fig. 84
). Up to 15 striae beyond the end of the raphe (
Figs 84, 85
). Internally, the central raphe endings curve slightly, without cuniculi (
Fig. 87
), helictoglossa at apical termini (
Figs 85, 86
). Several copulae, each with two rows of pores, larger pores on each band in the central area (
Figs 88–90
).

Description:—
Valves straight, lanceolate, with acute apices, length 110–133 μm, width 13–14 μm (
Figs 91–93
). Living cells with lobed, plate-like plastids along the girdle sides (
Fig. 93
). Striae decussate, oblique striae crossing at ~60°, longitudinal striae deflected around the central area; transverse striae 
26 in
10 μm (
Figs 92, 94, 96
). Areolae duplex, as seen internally, except single in the central area (
Figs 96, 100
), opening externally as single apically-oriented slits (
Figs 94, 95, 98, 99
). A line of smaller areolae alternating with those of regular size in a line along each side of the raphe-sternum (
Figs 96, 100
, arrows); a line of small areolae extending around the valve border (
Figs 96, 100
) except around the apex, where zero, one, or two isolated areolae occurred (
Figs 97, 101, 102
). Raphe path straight, central. External raphe slit slightly sinuous near central area, raphe branches ending in small pores deflected to the same side, nonoverlapping (
Figs 94, 98
). Internal central raphe endings straight, bordered by slender, smooth, equal central bars (
type
1 of 

Cardinal 
et al.
1989

, as is 

P. intermedium

). Terminal raphe endings slightly deflected externally, internally straight and ending in a helictoglossa.
